    "\n",
    "The code below attempts to simulate a longitudinal attack on the weights of a trained model. As to not be identified as compromised, the model has its weights slowly modified over time post-deployment, where a handful of weights are slightly adjusted every few days. \n",
    "\n",
    "The result of this prolonged attack is an eventual deterioration of model performance as the cumulative impact of weight changes compound into a greater and greater impact. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Implementation**\n",
    "\n",
    "- The validation data horizon is used to represent predictions made post deployment over the course of 212 days. This represents the model 'in use'\n",
    "- For each of these 212 days, a Poisson distribution is sampled to determine how many weight matrices will be perturbed that day (`n_perturbs`). When `n_perturbs = 0` is sampled, no changes to the model are made for that day.\n",
    "- When `n_perturbs > 0`, randomly sample `n_perturbs` weight matrix indices without replacement. These indices represent which matrices to perturb.\n",
    "- For each of these weight matrices chosen for that day:\n",
    "    -  Randomly sample a perturbation magnitude (`wgt_magnitude`) to apply on the matrix.\n",
    "    -  Use the average gradient wrt loss corresponding to the selected matrix as the weight vector that will be subtracted from the original, flattened target matrix. Make the gradient negative before subtraction.\n",
    "    -  Details on the vector operations used for the perturbation are found in the docstring of the `perturb_weights` function above.\n",
    "- Replace the original target weight matrices with the newly perturbed versions, but keep all other matrices the same as before.\n",
    "- The attacked model is used to make predictions on the given day with the newly perturbed weight matrices.\n",
